{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/how-did-twitter-react-to-the-coronavirus-pandemic-2857592b449a", "time": 1683004916.124179, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/how-did-twitter-react-to-the-coronavirus-pandemic-2857592b449a/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "How did Twitter react to the Coronavirus pandemic? | by fylim | Towards Data Science", "h1": "How did Twitter react to the Coronavirus pandemic?", "description": "The recent Coronavirus/COVID 19 outbreaks have recently been declared a global emergency. As we start practicing social distancing, work from home to control the virus spread, I decided to use my\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "http://towardsdatascience.com/", "anchor_text": "Towards Data Science", "paragraph_index": 17}, {"url": "https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/situation-reports", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 17}], "all_paragraphs": ["The recent Coronavirus/COVID 19 outbreaks have recently been declared a global emergency. As we start practicing social distancing, work from home to control the virus spread, I decided to use my spare time to look into what people are talking about the pandemic online.", "For this article, 15,000 tweets with #Coronavirus and #COVID19 between January 30 to March 15 in 2020 were extracted for analysis.", "There are many R packages that allow you to extract tweets into usable data types for analysis. Before you use the package in R, make sure that you have an API account on twitter that allows you to extract the tweets. The block of code below extracts all texts with #Coronavirus and #COVID19 twitted between January 30 to March 15 in 2020.", "Before we jump into mining the tweets, let\u2019s look at a few most favorited and retweeted texts:", "First, the dataset is transformed into a corpus, a collection of documents (datatype) recognized in R. Then, the corpus is pre-processed with making all characters lowercase, removing all punctuation marks, white spaces, and common words (stop words).", "After the corpus is pre-processed, I use the tokenization method to grab the word combinations. If you are not familiar with tokenization, this method can help to extract useful phrases that lead to some additional insights.", "One of the easiest ways to explore data is with frequency analysis. Although not difficult, in sentiment analysis this simple method can be surprisingly illuminating.", "Word frequency of bi-grams (2-word) and tri-grams (3-word) can give us better insights from the dataset we are analyzing. Simply update the tokenizer function\u2019s min and max to the number of word gram you would like to investigate to get the following results:", "Based on the bigram and trigram list, we know that people are talking about:", "Sentiment analysis helps us understand people\u2019s feelings towards a specific subject. It is done by identifying, categorizing opinions and transforming the words into actionable insights.", "First, we need a tibble (datatype) to break the tweets\u2019 sentences into words for further analysis.", "Polarity scores help us make quantitative judgments about the feelings of some text. In short, we categorize words from the tweets into positive and negative types and give them a score for analysis.", "The polarity scoring tells us if a chunk of text together is negative, neutral, or positive. If the score is close to or equal to 1, we would consider the body of text as positive and vice versa.", "Next, we can also categorize words using polarity scores, putting the words into the \u2018positive\u2019 or \u2018negative\u2019 basket. First, we assign each word in the extracted tweets a polarity score. Then, we filter the dataset to get only words with a polarity score of 80 or more.", "To get a broader picture of how positive and negative words are used, I assigned the words with a sentiment using the \u2018bing\u2019 lexicon and do a simple count to generate the top 10 most common positive and negative words used in the extracted tweets.", "Classifying the words into different types of emotions also helps us understand how people are feeling towards a subject, which in this case, is the Coronavirus pandemic.", "Other than categorizing the words into two categories (positive and negative) only, we can also label the words into multiple emotional states. In this section, we group the words into ten groups and pick the top 10 most common words in each of the group.", "Note from the editors: Towards Data Science is a Medium publication primarily based on the study of data science and machine learning. We are not health professionals or epidemiologists, and the opinions of this article should not be interpreted as professional advice. To learn more about the coronavirus pandemic, you can click here.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "is passionate about transforming texts into data points #NaturalLanguageProcessing"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F2857592b449a&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fhow-did-twitter-react-to-the-coronavirus-pandemic-2857592b449a&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fhow-did-twitter-react-to-the-coronavirus-pandemic-2857592b449a&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redir